System_InstalledFeatures:: ###[BEGIN]
System_InstalledFeatures:: ###Between System_InstalledCapabilities, System_InstalledFeatured, and System_InstalledSoftware, we collect a complete list of installed software -- from Microsoft and others.
System_InstalledFeatures:: ###Get-WindowsFeature is part of the Server Manager module for PowerShell and is therefore only relevant on Server operating systems.
System_InstalledFeatures:: ###Processing Command:  "System is not a Server ($systemtype).  Get-WindowsFeatures was not run." 
System_InstalledFeatures::System is not a Server (Windows11).  Get-WindowsFeatures was not run.
System_InstalledFeatures:: ###Between System_InstalledCapabilities, System_InstalledFeatured, and System_InstalledSoftware, we collect a complete list of installed software -- from Microsoft and others.
System_InstalledFeatures:: ###Get-WindowsOptionalFeature provides the list of Optional Features (see Apps and Features --> Optional Features).
System_InstalledFeatures:: ###Processing Command:  Get-WindowsOptionalFeature -Online | Where-Object {$_.State -eq 'Enabled'} | format-table -Autosize 
System_InstalledFeatures::
System_InstalledFeatures::FeatureName                                   State
System_InstalledFeatures::-----------                                   -----
System_InstalledFeatures::Printing-PrintToPDFServices-Features        Enabled
System_InstalledFeatures::Printing-XPSServices-Features               Enabled
System_InstalledFeatures::MSRDC-Infrastructure                        Enabled
System_InstalledFeatures::MicrosoftWindowsPowerShellV2Root            Enabled
System_InstalledFeatures::MicrosoftWindowsPowerShellV2                Enabled
System_InstalledFeatures::WCF-Services45                              Enabled
System_InstalledFeatures::WCF-TCP-PortSharing45                       Enabled
System_InstalledFeatures::MediaPlayback                               Enabled
System_InstalledFeatures::WindowsMediaPlayer                          Enabled
System_InstalledFeatures::SmbDirect                                   Enabled
System_InstalledFeatures::NetFx4-AdvSrvs                              Enabled
System_InstalledFeatures::SearchEngine-Client-Package                 Enabled
System_InstalledFeatures::Microsoft-RemoteDesktopConnection           Enabled
System_InstalledFeatures::WorkFolders-Client                          Enabled
System_InstalledFeatures::Printing-Foundation-Features                Enabled
System_InstalledFeatures::Printing-Foundation-InternetPrinting-Client Enabled
System_InstalledFeatures::VirtualMachinePlatform                      Enabled
System_InstalledFeatures::Microsoft-Windows-Subsystem-Linux           Enabled
System_InstalledFeatures::
System_InstalledFeatures::
System_InstalledFeatures:: ###[END]
System_InstalledHotfixes:: ###This section provides a list of all hotfixes that have been installed.  Reviewing these results is a critical part of analyzing patch management practices.
System_InstalledHotfixes:: ###Look at 'System_PendingWindowsUpdates' for a list of things that still need to be installed.
System_InstalledHotfixes:: ###IMPORTANT NOTE: Get-HotFix is not 100% reliable.  Whether it reports on the HF action depends on the manner used to install the HF.  Notably, it does not capture
System_InstalledHotfixes:: ###all HFs installed by WindowsUpdate.  We will use two methods to gather HF info, hoping to improve the qualify of collected data.
System_InstalledHotfixes:: ###The first method uses the PowerShell "Get-Hotfix" command.  The second queries the Windows Update Service directly.
System_InstalledHotfixes:: ###[BEGIN]
System_InstalledHotfixes:: ###Processing Command:  Get-HotFix -ErrorAction silentlycontinue | Select-Object -Property Description, HotFixID, InstalledOn | Sort-Object -Descending -Property InstalledOn | Format-Table -AutoSize 
System_InstalledHotfixes::
System_InstalledHotfixes::Description     HotFixID  InstalledOn          
System_InstalledHotfixes::-----------     --------  -----------          
System_InstalledHotfixes::Security Update KB5058405 5/14/2025 12:00:00 AM
System_InstalledHotfixes::Security Update KB5058528 5/14/2025 12:00:00 AM
System_InstalledHotfixes::Update          KB5054980 4/12/2025 12:00:00 AM
System_InstalledHotfixes::Update          KB5027397 3/1/2024 12:00:00 AM 
System_InstalledHotfixes::Security Update KB5012170 2/17/2023 12:00:00 AM
System_InstalledHotfixes::
System_InstalledHotfixes::
System_InstalledHotfixes:: ###[END]
System_WindowsUpdateHistory:: ###[BEGIN]
System_WindowsUpdateHistory:: ###This section collects all available Windows Update Service history.  This /should/ help with filling in the gaps where "Get-Hotfix" doesn't
System_WindowsUpdateHistory:: ###accurately report hotfix installation history (see note on System_InstalledHotfixes section).
System_WindowsUpdateHistory:: ###NOTE: This will grab /all/ Windows Update History, including for instance daily Defender updates.  That might be helpful as evidence that
System_WindowsUpdateHistory:: ###anti-virus tools are being updated daily.  Basically, if it was action taken by WUS, then it /should/ be in this log.
System_WindowsUpdateHistory:: ###Processing Command:  $Searcher.QueryHistory(0, $historyCount) | Select-Object @{name="Operation"; expression={switch($_.operation){ 1 {"Installation"}; 2 {"Uninstallation"}; 3 {"Other"}}}}, Date, Title

System_InstalledSoftware:: ###[BEGIN]
System_InstalledSoftware:: ###Between System_InstalledCapabilities, System_InstalledFeatured, and System_InstalledSoftware, we collect a complete list of installed software -- from Microsoft and others.
System_InstalledSoftware:: ###System_InstalledSoftware provides a list of all software installed including from 3rd party sources.
System_InstalledSoftware:: ###For 3rd party software, check each product to make sure that versions are reasonably maintained.
System_InstalledSoftware:: ###Processing Command:  Get-ItemProperty "HKLM:\Software\Wow6432Node\Microsoft\Windows\CurrentVersion\Uninstall\*" -ErrorAction silentlycontinue | Select-Object DisplayName, DisplayVersion, Publisher, InstallDate | format-table -Autosize

System_PendingWindowsUpdates:: ###[BEGIN]
System_PendingWindowsUpdates:: ###System_PendingWindowsUpdates captures the results of an attempt to run Windows Update.  It will work identically to running the WU Control Panel, including using WSUS servers if configured.
System_PendingWindowsUpdates:: ###This should be your go-to section for evaluating what MS-provided updates are waiting to be installed and has the same level of accuracy as running Windows Update.
System_PendingWindowsUpdates:: ###If Internet connectivity is impaired and there is no WSUS server, this will fail.
System_PendingWindowsUpdates:: ###Explanation of the fields is provided from https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/win32/api/wuapi/nn-wuapi-iupdate
System_PendingWindowsUpdates:: ###     DeploymentChangeTime    Date when this item was made available as an update.
System_PendingWindowsUpdates:: ###     AutoSelectOnWebSites    1 if this item is autoselected by WU to be installed.
System_PendingWindowsUpdates:: ###     IsHidden                1 if this update has been hidden by the user.
System_PendingWindowsUpdates:: ###     IsMandatory             1 if this update provides enhancements to the Windows Update Agent infrastructure.
System_PendingWindowsUpdates:: ###This provides all available updates, even the ones that are optional or marked as driver updates that would only be installed if experiencing a problem.
System_PendingWindowsUpdates:: ###It's probably best to focus on the AutoSelectOnWebsites field.
System_PendingWindowsUpdates:: ###Processing Command:  "Found $($updates.Count) updates!" 
System_PendingWindowsUpdates::Found 2 updates!
System_PendingWindowsUpdates:: ###Processing Command:  $updates | Format-Table Title, LastDeploymentChangeTime, AutoSelectOnWebSites, IsHidden, IsMandatory -Autosize 
System_PendingWindowsUpdates::
System_PendingWindowsUpdates::Title                                                                                                                     LastDeploymentChangeTime AutoSelectOnWebSites IsHidden IsMandatory
System_PendingWindowsUpdates::-----                                                                                                                     ------------------------ -------------------- -------- -----------
System_PendingWindowsUpdates::2025-04 Cumulative Update Preview for .NET Framework 3.5 and 4.8.1 for Windows 11, version 23H2 for x64 (KB5056580)       4/22/2025 12:00:00 AM                   False    False       False
System_PendingWindowsUpdates::Security Intelligence Update for Microsoft Defender Antivirus - KB2267602 (Version 1.429.173.0) - Current Channel (Broad) 5/25/2025 12:00:00 AM                    True    False       False
System_PendingWindowsUpdates::
System_PendingWindowsUpdates::
System_PendingWindowsUpdates:: ###[END]
System_RunningProcesses:: ###[BEGIN]
System_RunningProcesses:: ###A list of all of running processes on the system.  This is useful when looking for anti-virus, user programs and really anything else that's currently listed in the Task Manager.
System_RunningProcesses:: ###NOTE: This is displayed in LIST format because PowerShell does some funny things when formatting this information as a table.
System_RunningProcesses:: ###Processing Command:  Get-Process * -IncludeUserName | Select-Object ProcessName, Path, Company, Product, ID, Username | Sort-Object Company, Product | Format-List

System_RDPEncryption:: ###[BEGIN]
System_RDPEncryption:: ###This section pulls together a couple of settings for how Windows handles TDP encryption.
System_RDPEncryption:: ###First, we collect the GPO setting from the registry for the source of RDP's encryption.  Reference the "Ensure 'Require use of specific security layer for RDP connections'" CIS benchmark items.
System_RDPEncryption:: ###     SecurityLayer = 0       Use RDP Security Layer (this is sub-par)
System_RDPEncryption:: ###     SecurityLayer = 1       Negotiate the security layer (not ideal)
System_RDPEncryption:: ###     SecurityLayer = 2       Use SSL/TLS Security Layer (best)
System_RDPEncryption:: ###If the immediately following results are blank, then this GPO is not set, which results in "Negotiate" behavior.
System_RDPEncryption:: ###Processing Command:  Get-ItemProperty "HKLM:\SOFTWARE\Policies\Microsoft\Windows NT\Terminal Services" | Select-Object SecurityLayer | Format-List 
System_RDPEncryption:: ###When GPO is configured to "RDP" or when negotiated parameters result in using "RDP Security Layer", the next result provides the RDP Encryption setting.
System_RDPEncryption:: ###  1 = Low
System_RDPEncryption:: ###  2 = Negotiated
System_RDPEncryption:: ###  3 = High
System_RDPEncryption:: ###RDP should not be used as the security layer (see above), but if it must be used, then only "High Security" should be used.
System_RDPEncryption:: ###Processing Command:  Get-ItemProperty -Path "HKLM:\SYSTEM\CurrentControlSet\Control\Terminal Server\WinStations\RDP-Tcp" -ErrorAction silentlycontinue | Select-Object MinEncryptionLevel | Format-List 
System_RDPEncryption::
System_RDPEncryption::
System_RDPEncryption::MinEncryptionLevel : 2
System_RDPEncryption::
System_RDPEncryption::
System_RDPEncryption::
System_RDPEncryption:: ###[END]
System_RemoteAssistanceConfig:: ###[BEGIN]
System_RemoteAssistanceConfig:: ###Remote Assistance comes in two varieties -- Unsolicited (as in Help Desk-directred) and User-requested.  Both forms are disabled by default on both servers and workstations.
System_RemoteAssistanceConfig:: ###NOTE: **REMOTE ASSISTANCE SHOULD BE DISABLED** RESULTS SHOULD BE 0 or NON-EXISTANT
System_RemoteAssistanceConfig:: ###Reference CIS Windows Server or Windows 10 Benchmarks section 18.8.36 for more information.
System_RemoteAssistanceConfig:: ###First, the policy configuration:
System_RemoteAssistanceConfigPolicy:: ###Processing Command:  Get-ItemProperty -Path "HKLM:\SOFTWARE\Policies\Microsoft\Windows NT\Terminal Services" -ErrorAction silentlycontinue | Select-Object fAllowUnsolicited, fAllowToGetHelp | Format-List 
System_RemoteAssistanceConfigRunning:: ###The running configuration:
System_RemoteAssistanceConfigRunning:: ###Processing Command:  Get-ItemProperty -Path "HKLM:\SYSTEM\CurrentControlSet\Control\Remote Assistance\" -ErrorAction silentlycontinue | Select-Object fAllowUnsolicited, fAllowToGetHelp | Format-List 
System_RemoteAssistanceConfigRunning::
System_RemoteAssistanceConfigRunning::
System_RemoteAssistanceConfigRunning::fAllowUnsolicited : 
System_RemoteAssistanceConfigRunning::fAllowToGetHelp   : 1
System_RemoteAssistanceConfigRunning::
System_RemoteAssistanceConfigRunning::
System_RemoteAssistanceConfigRunning::
System_RemoteAssistanceConfigRunning:: ###[END]
System_ScreensaverConfig:: ###[BEGIN]
System_ScreensaverConfig:: ###Using the screensaver is the most common way of locking the computer after inactivity.  Many audit standards (e.g. PCI) look for no more than 15 minutes (900 seconds), which seems reasonable.
System_ScreensaverConfig:: ###There might be other methods of achieving this (such as through Power Settings), but these registry keys related to using GPO and to user-directed configurations respectively.
System_ScreensaverConfig:: ###If these settings aren't conclusive or contradict what the customer says, you might need to dig in further.
System_ScreenSaverConfigGPO:: ###If this registry query comes back blank, GPO is not used to enforce screensaver settings
System_ScreenSaverConfigGPO:: ###     ScreenSaveActive        Is the screensaver enabled
System_ScreenSaverConfigGPO:: ###     ScreenSaverIsSecure     Requires a password to unlock the screensaver
System_ScreenSaverConfigGPO:: ###     ScreenSaverTimeOut      Inactivity period in seconds before the screensaver kicks in (900 seconds = 15 minutes)
System_ScreenSaverConfigGPO:: ###Processing Command:  Get-ItemProperty -Path "HKCU:\Software\Policies\Microsoft\Windows\Control Panel\Desktop" -ErrorAction silentlycontinue | Select-Object ScreenSaveActive, ScreenSaverIsSecure, ScreenSaveTimeOut | Format-List 
System_ScreenSaverConfigRunning:: ###Processing Command:  Get-ItemProperty -Path "HKCU:\Control Panel\Desktop" -ErrorAction silentlycontinue | Select-Object ScreenSaveActive, ScreenSaverIsSecure, ScreenSaveTimeOut | Format-List 
System_ScreenSaverConfigRunning::
System_ScreenSaverConfigRunning::
System_ScreenSaverConfigRunning::ScreenSaveActive    : 1
System_ScreenSaverConfigRunning::ScreenSaverIsSecure : 0
System_ScreenSaverConfigRunning::ScreenSaveTimeOut   : 60
System_ScreenSaverConfigRunning::
System_ScreenSaverConfigRunning::
System_ScreenSaverConfigRunning::
System_ScreenSaverConfigRunning:: ###In addition to the settings described above in System_ScreenSaverConfigGPO:
System_ScreenSaverConfigRunning:: ###     ScreenSaverGracePeriod  The period of time after the screensaver activates where the user can cause movement to cancel the screen saver.
System_ScreenSaverConfigRunning:: ###                             If the following results are blank, the default is 5 seconds
System_ScreenSaverConfigRunning:: ###Processing Command:  Get-ItemProperty -Path "HKLM:\SOFTWARE\Microsoft\Windows NT\CurrentVersion\Winlogon" -ErrorAction silentlycontinue | Select-Object ScreenSaverGracePeriod | Format-List 
System_ScreenSaverConfigRunning::
System_ScreenSaverConfigRunning::
System_ScreenSaverConfigRunning::ScreenSaverGracePeriod : 
System_ScreenSaverConfigRunning::
System_ScreenSaverConfigRunning::
System_ScreenSaverConfigRunning::
System_ScreenSaverConfigRunning:: ###[END]

System_SNMPConfig:: ###[BEGIN]
System_SNMPConfig:: ###Processing Command:  Get-Service snmp -ErrorAction silentlycontinue 
System_SNMPConfig:: ###A blank PermittedManagers means that SNMP packets will be accepted from any source.
System_SNMPConfig:: ###Processing Command:  Get-ItemProperty -path "HKLM:\SYSTEM\CurrentControlSet\Services\SNMP\Parameters\PermittedManagers" -ErrorAction silentlycontinue | Format-List 
System_SNMPConfig:: ###Processing Command:  Get-ItemProperty -path "HKLM:\SYSTEM\CurrentControlSet\Services\SNMP\Parameters\RFC1156Agent" -ErrorAction silentlycontinue | Select-Object sysContact, SysLocation | Format-List 
System_SNMPConfig:: ###Values for each listed community string are as follows:
System_SNMPConfig:: ###  16 - Read-Create
System_SNMPConfig:: ###  8 - Read-Write
System_SNMPConfig:: ###  4 - Read-Only
System_SNMPConfig:: ###  2 - Notify
System_SNMPConfig:: ###  1 - None
System_SNMPConfig:: ###Processing Command:  Get-ItemProperty -path "HKLM:\SYSTEM\CurrentControlSet\Services\SNMP\Parameters\ValidCommunities" -ErrorAction silentlycontinue 
System_SNMPConfig:: ###[END]
System_WindowsUpdateConfig:: ###[BEGIN]
System_WindowsUpdateConfig:: ###Interpreting Windows Update settings from: http://techgenix.com/Registry-Keys-Tweaking-Windows-Update-Part1/
System_WindowsUpdateConfig:: ###WUServer will provide the update source if using WSUS.  If not set, WSUS is not being used to receive updates.
System_WindowsUpdateConfig:: ###Processing Command:  Get-ItemProperty -path "HKLM:\SOFTWARE\Policies\Microsoft\Windows\WindowsUpdate\" -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue 
System_WindowsUpdateConfig:: ###AUOptions key means the following
System_WindowsUpdateConfig:: ###  2 - Agent notifies user prior to downloading updates
System_WindowsUpdateConfig:: ###  3 - Automatic download with user notification prior to install
System_WindowsUpdateConfig:: ###  4 - Automatic download and install according to schedule (look for ScheduledInstallDay and ScheduledInstallTime keys)
System_WindowsUpdateConfig:: ###  5 - Automatic updates are required with some user configurability
System_WindowsUpdateConfig:: ###NoAutoUpdate=1 disables automatic updates altogether
System_WindowsUpdateConfig:: ###If the following registry paths are not found, then system updates are managed through another method (e.g. MDM)
System_WindowsUpdateConfig:: ###Processing Command:  Get-ItemProperty -path "HKLM:\SOFTWARE\Policies\Microsoft\Windows\WindowsUpdate\AU" -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue | format-list 
System_WindowsUpdateConfig:: ###Here are some additional settings that might be useful, especially if the previous command didn't return any results
System_WindowsUpdateConfig:: ###Processing Command:  Get-ItemProperty -path "HKLM:\SOFTWARE\Microsoft\Windows\CurrentVersion\WindowsUpdate" -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue | format-list 
System_WindowsUpdateConfig::
System_WindowsUpdateConfig::

System_WindowsUpdateConfig::LastTaskOperationHandle : 5
System_WindowsUpdateConfig::SusClientId             : bfb756da-871b-4560-8f16-c32b9e389230
System_WindowsUpdateConfig::SusClientIdValidation   : {6, 2, 80, 1...}
System_WindowsUpdateConfig::UpdateDesiredVisibility : 0
System_WindowsUpdateConfig::PSPath                  : Microsoft.PowerShell.Core\Registry::HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\SOFTWARE\Microsoft\Windows\CurrentVersion\WindowsUpdate
System_WindowsUpdateConfig::PSParentPath            : Microsoft.PowerShell.Core\Registry::HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\SOFTWARE\Microsoft\Windows\CurrentVersion
System_WindowsUpdateConfig::PSChildName             : WindowsUpdate
System_WindowsUpdateConfig::PSDrive                 : HKLM
System_WindowsUpdateConfig::PSProvider              : Microsoft.PowerShell.Core\Registry

Networking_LanmanServerConfig:: ###[BEGIN]
Networking_LanmanServerConfig:: ###LanManager is responsible for providing the SMB-based file sharing on Windows servers.  There are both "SmbServer" and "SmbClient" components.
Networking_LanmanServerConfig:: ###   EnableSMBxProtocol              Enable/Disable specific version of the SMB protocol.  No specific recommendations.
Networking_LanmanServerConfig:: ###   AutoDisconnectTimeout           SMB sessions will disconnect after (minutes).  Default is 15 which is also CIS recommendation.
Networking_LanmanServerConfig:: ###   AutoShareServer/Workstation     Enable/disable the automatic shares.  Recommnedation is disabled.
Networking_LanmanServerConfig:: ###   EnableSecuritySignature         Enable the use of signed SMB (does not require it, but permits it.  Recommendation and default is "enabled".
Networking_LanmanServerConfig:: ###   NullSessionPipes/Shares         Shares and/or pipes that can be accessed through a null session.  Recommendation and default "blank".
Networking_LanmanServerConfig:: ###   RequireSecuritySignature        Require the use of signed SMB.  Default is "Disabled", but recommendation is "Enabled".
Networking_LanmanServerConfig:: ###   EnableInsecureGuestLogons       This setting disallows guest logons, which could be used directly or as a fall-back for access to network resources.  Recommnedation is Disabled.
Networking_LanmanServerConfig:: ###                                   Reference CIS Windows 10 and Windows Server 2016 benchmarks and https://docs.microsoft.com/en-US/troubleshoot/windows-server/networking/guest-access-in-smb2-is-disabled-by-default
Networking_LanmanServerConfig:: ###Processing Command:  Get-SmbServerConfiguration | Select-Object EnableSMB*,AutoDisconnectTimeout,AutoShareServer,AutoShareWorkstation,EnableSecuritySignature,NullSessionPipes,NullSessionShare,RequireSecuritySignature | Format-List 
Networking_LanmanServerConfig::
Networking_LanmanServerConfig::
Networking_LanmanServerConfig::EnableSMB1Protocol       : False
Networking_LanmanServerConfig::EnableSMB2Protocol       : True
Networking_LanmanServerConfig::EnableSMBQUIC            : True
Networking_LanmanServerConfig::AutoDisconnectTimeout    : 15
Networking_LanmanServerConfig::AutoShareServer          : True
Networking_LanmanServerConfig::AutoShareWorkstation     : True
Networking_LanmanServerConfig::EnableSecuritySignature  : False
Networking_LanmanServerConfig::NullSessionPipes         : 
Networking_LanmanServerConfig::NullSessionShare         : 
Networking_LanmanServerConfig::RequireSecuritySignature : False
Networking_LanmanServerConfig::
Networking_LanmanServerConfig::
Networking_LanmanServerConfig::
Networking_LanmanServerConfig:: ###[END]

Networking_ListeningServices:: ###[BEGIN]
Networking_ListeningServices:: ###Provide a list of all network listeners and the process that is listening on the port.  This is useful in a wide range of situations including:
Networking_ListeningServices:: ###   - Comparing listening services against documented lists of ports, protocols and services
Networking_ListeningServices:: ###   - Comparing against hardening documentation
Networking_ListeningServices:: ###   - Determining if there are any insecure ports, protocols or services in use that require additional protections.
Networking_ListeningServices:: ###Processing Command:  Get-NetworkListeners | Where-Object { $_.state -eq "LISTENING" } | Format-Table -AutoSize

Networking_WinRM:: ###[BEGIN]
Networking_WinRM:: ###Windows Remote Monitoring (WinRM) provides remote management capabilities (reference: WS-MAN protocol) as well as PowerShell Remoting features
Networking_WinRM:: ###There a few settings that should be evaluated to ensure that remote access is properly secured and encrypted
Networking_WinRM:: ###  - Transport: Can be HTTP or HTTPS, but regardless of the setting, WinRM performs encryption according to the 'AllowUnencrypted' setting below
Networking_WinRM:: ###  - AllowUnuncrypted: This defaults to False, which ensures that message-level encryption is enforced for the WinRM protocol even if HTTP is used as the transport
Networking_WinRM:: ###  - Auth methods: Various authentication methods enabled on the WinRM server
Networking_WinRM:: ###  - ListeningOn: The IP addresses where the server is listening for WinRM connections
Networking_WinRM:: ###  - AllowRemoteAccess: Pretty much what it says
Networking_WinRM:: ###  - AllowRemoteShellAccess: Allows PowerShell remote shell connections
Networking_WinRM:: ###[END]
Time_W32TimeRegistry:: ###[BEGIN]
Time_W32TimeRegistry:: ###Two approaches are used to pull time synchronization settings.  The first approach pulls settings directly from the registry.
Time_W32TimeRegistry:: ###The second approach (in the Time_W32TimeConfig section below) uses the w32tm command to pull active configurations.
Time_W32TimeRegistry:: ###Both sources should show similar information.  We may drop the registry method in the future.
Time_W32TimeRegistry:: ###Registry setting reference: https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows-server/networking/windows-time-service/windows-time-service-tools-and-settings#reference-windows-time-service-registry-entries
Time_W32TimeRegistry:: ###A few settings of particular note:
Time_W32TimeRegistry:: ###   AnnounceFlags               Controls whether this computer is marked as a reliable time server. A computer is not marked as reliable unless it is also marked as a time server.
Time_W32TimeRegistry:: ###   ClockAdjustmentAuditLimit   Specifies the smallest local clock adjustments that may be logged to the W32time service event log on the target computer.
Time_W32TimeRegistry:: ###   EventLogFlags               Controls which events that the time service logs. 0x1 = Time jump.  0x2 = Source change
Time_W32TimeRegistry-Config:: ###Processing Command:  Get-ItemProperty -Path "HKLM:\SYSTEM\CurrentControlSet\Services\W32Time\Config" -ErrorAction silentlycontinue 
Time_W32TimeRegistry-Config::
Time_W32TimeRegistry-Config::

Time_W32TimeRegistry-Config::ClockHoldoverPeriod       : 50000
Time_W32TimeRegistry-Config::EventLogFlags             : 2
Time_W32TimeRegistry-Config::FrequencyCorrectRate      : 4
Time_W32TimeRegistry-Config::HoldPeriod                : 5
Time_W32TimeRegistry-Config::LargePhaseOffset          : 50000000

Time_W32TimeConfig:: ###[BEGIN]
Time_W32TimeConfig:: ###Provides detailed information on the configuration of the Windows Time Service (W32Time).
Time_W32TimeConfig:: ###NOTE: For each of the "TimeW32Time*" checks, the "w32tm" command will complete successfully only if the W32Time service is running.
Time_W32TimeConfig:: ###In  many situations, the Windows Time Service starts when needed and the stops.  For instance, Windows 10 desktop computers will produce
Time_W32TimeConfig:: ###sporadic results.  For servers, the service is more likely to be running especially if it's a domain controller or providing NTP to other systems.
Time_W32TimeConfig:: ###Reference this page for additional information the output from the W32TM command: https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows-server/networking/windows-time-service/windows-time-service-tools-and-settings
Time_W32TimeConfig:: ###Windows Time Service is running.  W32Tm results below are reliable.

AntiVirus_AVStatus:: ###   This would at least provide that A/V is running, even if other details need to tested manually.

AntiVirus_AVStatus::displayName  : Windows Defender
AntiVirus_AVStatus::productState : 397568
AntiVirus_AVStatus::
AntiVirus_AVStatus::
AntiVirus_AVStatus::
AntiVirus_AVStatus:: ###The following is known to work at least with Windows Defender on Windows 10 and Server 2016.  As other AV products
AntiVirus_AVStatus:: ###on other platforms were not available for testing, your mileage may vary.
AntiVirus_AVStatus:: ###Use this to determine if A/V is enabled for all types of protections and the update timestamps for various elements of the software.
AntiVirus_AVStatus:: ###If the results are blank, then the A/V product reports its health through another mechanism and you'll need to test it manually.
AntiVirus_AVStatus:: ###NOTE: The ProductState above and the ProductStatus below are two different items.  Interpretation of the ProductStatus below:
AntiVirus_AVStatus:: ###   Windows Defender: https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/graph/api/resources/intune-devices-windowsdefenderproductstatus.  A few codes of interest:
AntiVirus_AVStatus:: ###       1       Service Not Running
AntiVirus_AVStatus:: ###       32      AV Signature out of date.
AntiVirus_AVStatus:: ###       64      AS Signature out of date.
AntiVirus_AVStatus:: ###       4096    Product running in evaluation mode.
AntiVirus_AVStatus:: ###       8192    Product running in non-genuine Windows mode.
AntiVirus_AVStatus:: ###       16384   Product expired.
AntiVirus_AVStatus:: ###       524288  No status flags set (well-initialed state) NOTE: This is the desired state.  It means all is well.
AntiVirus_AVStatus:: ###       1048576 Platform is out of date.
AntiVirus_AVStatus:: ###       8388608 Signature or platform end of life is past or is impending.
AntiVirus_AVStatus:: ###Processing Command:  Get-WmiObject -namespace "root\Microsoft\SecurityClient" -query "SELECT * FROM AntimalwareHealthStatus" -ErrorAction silentlycontinue | Select-Object Name, *Version, *Enabled, *SignatureAge, *UpdateDateTime, Last*, ProductStatus, RealTimeScanDirection | Format-List

Logging_AuditLogConfig:: ###[BEGIN]
Logging_AuditLogConfig:: ###Provides registry settings for the application, system, and security Event Logs.
Logging_AuditLogConfig:: ###See https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/win32/eventlog/eventlog-key for details about what each item means.
Logging_AuditLogConfig:: ###NOTE: If log harvesting tools such as Splunk are used to collect Windows Event Logs in real-time, these settings don't carry as much importance.

Logging_EventLogSamples:: ###[BEGIN]
Logging_EventLogSamples:: ###Provides samples of Windows Event Logs (50 newest events).  Use this to test that event logs are being actively written to the Windows Event Log system.
Logging_EventLogSamples:: ###NOTE:  There are many tools that can collect the logs for centralized storage and analysis, but most -- if not all -- rely on the Event Log system in Windows.
Logging_EventLogSamples:: ###       If Event Log doesn't have the event, then it's unlikely that Splunk, FluentD or other collection agents will have the event.
Logging_EventLogSamples:: ###Event Logs captured include:
Logging_EventLogSamples:: ###   Application     Contains events logged by applications. For example, a database application might record a file error. The application developer decides which events to record.
Logging_EventLogSamples:: ###   Security        Contains events such as valid and invalid logon attempts, as well as events related to resource use such as creating, opening, or deleting files or other objects.
Logging_EventLogSamples:: ###   System 	        Contains events logged by system components, such as the failure of a driver or other system component to load during startup.
Logging_EventLogSamplesApplication:: ###Processing Command:  Get-EventLog $i -Newest 50 -ErrorAction Stop | format-table -Autosize
